  "summary": "During an investigation, Hueish questions Mr. Aggles regarding his son Jacques's behavior. Mr. Aggles explains that he and his wife decided to stop bailing Jacques out of trouble, which led to a confrontation where Jacques left the house angrily, threatening to return for money. Mr. Aggles admits he did not fear an attack but was shocked to learn Jacques was a suspect. \n\nGwendolyn Vaughn, a typist, confirms that Mrs. Aggles left the room around 6:53 PM. Gwendolyn left the house at 7:15 PM, noting that the sitting room door was ajar but she did not enter to say goodnight. On her walk home toward Red Lane, she recalls a car splashing mud on her at an intersection. Mr. Aggles mentions he may have heard a doorbell ring after his wife left the room, though he is uncertain. He also reveals he was unaware that Jacques had married, a fact that surprised him when Jacques's wife arrived the following day.\n\nHester Aggles is questioned about her movements on the day of the incident. She states she left the house around 7:00 PM to attend a play at the Dreymouth Theatre. She claims she went to her mother's room to ask for money for gasoline. While she initially suggests Mrs. Corsden gave her the money, she later clarifies that she took money from Coulston after Mrs. Aggles told her to do so. Hester notes that her last interaction with her mother involved saying goodnight while her mother sat at her desk. Corston Lindström adds that she saw Hester drive past her toward the main road as she was walking toward the village.",
